Rules:
- Pick the single most specific primitive_key that fits the bug.
- Prefer library-api when the surface is unclear but the bug lives in a library API.
- For an open redirect: primitive=open_redirect; surface=library-api (or network for an HTTP service).
- Use caller_controls for what the external caller shapes. Use parameter_control
  and trusted_caller_actions for extra local preconditions; do not repeat bytes
  there when a normal public caller supplies the trigger bytes directly.
- If reproducing the crash requires the caller to install a callback — a memory
  allocator/free or lock hook, a match/substitute callout, a recursion/resource
  guard, a comparator, or an enumeration callback — that frees, destroys, or
  mutates an object the in-flight library call still owns, the precondition is a
  caller call-sequence: set caller_controls to "call-sequence" and
  trusted_caller_actions to "callback ordering". Input bytes may control WHEN the
  callback fires, but the destructive callback is caller-installed code, not
  attacker bytes — so do not classify caller_controls as "bytes".
- Use trigger_source "call-sequence" ONLY for a purely local call-ordering
  trigger with no attacker byte/content path. If input bytes drive the trigger
  at all — including merely controlling callback timing — keep trigger_source
  "bytes" and record the local precondition in caller_controls instead;
  mislabelling a byte-reachable bug as call-sequence would wrongly localise it
  (AV:L) and under-score it.
- For resource/algorithmic-exhaustion primitives (stack_exhaustion,
  dos_amplification, regex_dos, memory_leak, oom), classify trigger_source by
  the exhausting quantity, not the field values. The exhausting quantity is the
  nesting depth, element/iteration count, total size, or backtracking steps that
  drives the blow-up. If the library's own input path provably bounds it below
  the level that exhausts — e.g. a parser nesting or size limit lower than the
  depth or count the crash needs — attacker-supplied bytes cannot reach the
  threshold, and only a trusted caller building the structure through the API
  can: set trigger_source to "call-sequence". Keep trigger_source "bytes" only
  when the quantity is itself attacker-driven through input, e.g. catastrophic
  regex backtracking from an attacker pattern/subject or deep nesting a parser
  accepts with no lower limit. Controlling the field VALUES is not controlling
  the exhausting quantity.
- Output JSON only, no prose, no markdown fences.

